  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Yugasa Temple
  author: Kim Ji-dae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The temple rests in mist and glow, beyond all worldly care.
    On tangled peaks, emerald drops pool thick as autumn deepens.
    Between the clouds, steep paths stretch six or seven leagues,
    While distant ridges at heaven's edge layer a thousand—ten thousand folds.

    Tea finished, the crescent moon hangs from the pine-thatched eaves.
    The dharma talk ends; cool wind stirs the bell's last cry.
    The stream must surely laugh at an official such as I,
    Who seeks to wash away the dust of office, yet cannot.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'official' (玉腰客) refers to the poet himself, suggesting he held a court position before seeking refuge in the temple.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'red dust' (紅塵) is a Buddhist metaphor for the defilements of worldly life and desire.
  - key: ''
    value: The final paradox—desiring to wash away worldly stains yet unable to do so—captures the tension between spiritual aspiration and human limitation that defines the poet's condition.
